module.exports = [
  [137, "The Fall of the Roman Empire", "历史", 2, "The fall of the Western Roman Empire in 476 CE marked one of the most significant transitions in world history. For centuries, Rome had been the dominant power in Europe, North Africa, and the Middle East, but a combination of internal decay and external pressures ultimately brought the empire to an end.\n\nInternal factors contributed significantly to Rome's decline. Political corruption became rampant, with emperors frequently assassinated and replaced. Economic troubles included inflation, heavy taxation, and a widening gap between rich and poor. The reliance on slave labor discouraged technological innovation and weakened the free citizenry. Military recruitment increasingly depended on mercenaries whose loyalty was questionable.\n\nExternal pressures proved devastating. Germanic tribes including the Visigoths, Vandals, and Ostrogoths launched repeated invasions. The Huns, led by Attila, pushed other tribes into Roman territory. In 410 CE, the Visigoths sacked Rome itself, shaking the empire to its core. The Vandals captured North Africa, depriving Rome of its vital grain supply.\n\nThe Eastern Roman Empire, centered on Constantinople, survived for nearly a thousand more years as the Byzantine Empire. The fall of the Western Empire ushered in the Middle Ages in Europe, a period of political fragmentation, population decline, and cultural transformation that would last until the Renaissance. The legacy of Roman law, language, and institutions continued to shape Western civilization long after the empire itself had vanished.",
  "西罗马帝国于公元476年的覆灭是世界历史上最重要的转折之一。几个世纪以来，罗马一直是欧洲、北非和中东的主导力量，但内部衰败和外部压力的结合最终导致了帝国的终结。\n\n内部因素对罗马的衰亡贡献显著。政治腐败变得猖獗，皇帝频繁被暗杀和替换。经济困难包括通货膨胀、重税和贫富差距扩大。对外来雇佣兵的依赖削弱了军事忠诚。\n\n外部压力证明是毁灭性的。日耳曼部落包括西哥特人、汪达尔人和东哥特人发动了反复入侵。公元410年，西哥特人洗劫了罗马。\n\n东罗马帝国以君士坦丁堡为中心，作为拜占庭帝国又存续了近千年。西帝国的覆灭开启了欧洲的中世纪。罗马法律、语言和制度的遗产在西帝国消失后仍继续塑造着西方文明。",
  330, [["When did the Western Roman Empire fall?","27 BCE","476 CE","1453 CE","100 CE","B","文章指出西罗马帝国于公元476年覆灭。"],["What internal factor contributed to Rome's decline?","Excessive technological innovation","Political corruption, economic troubles, and reliance on slave labor","Too many citizens","Strong military loyalty","B","文章指出政治腐败、经济困难和依赖奴隶劳动是内部衰亡因素。"],["Which group sacked Rome in 410 CE?","The Huns","The Vandals","The Visigoths","The Ostrogoths","C","文章指出公元410年西哥特人洗劫了罗马。"],["What happened to the Eastern Roman Empire?","It fell at the same time as the Western Empire","It survived for nearly a thousand more years as the Byzantine Empire","It conquered the Western Empire","It moved to Africa","B","文章指出东罗马帝国作为拜占庭帝国又存续了近千年。"]]],
  [138, "The Silk Road and Cultural Exchange", "历史", 1, "The Silk Road was a network of trade routes connecting East Asia with the Middle East, Africa, and Europe. Named after the lucrative Chinese silk trade, these routes facilitated not only commerce but also the exchange of ideas, religions, technologies, and diseases between civilizations for over 1,500 years.\n\nThe Silk Road was not a single road but a complex network of land and sea routes spanning thousands of miles. Merchants traveled in caravans for safety, stopping at oasis towns that grew into prosperous trading centers. The journey was perilous, crossing deserts, mountains, and bandit-infested territories.\n\nGoods traded along the Silk Road transformed societies on both ends. Chinese silk, spices, tea, and porcelain flowed westward, while glassware, wool, gold, and silver moved eastward. Perhaps more significant than goods were the ideas that traveled these routes. Buddhism spread from India to China and East Asia. Islam expanded into Central Asia. Paper-making technology traveled from China to the Islamic world and eventually to Europe.\n\nThe Silk Road also transmitted less welcome travelers. The Black Death, which killed an estimated 75 to 200 million people in the fourteenth century, likely traveled along Silk Road routes from Central Asia to Europe. Despite such consequences, the Silk Road remains one of history's most important channels of cross-cultural exchange, demonstrating that contact between civilizations, while sometimes devastating, has fundamentally shaped human development.",
  "丝绸之路是连接东亚与中东、非洲和欧洲的贸易路线网络。以利润丰厚的中国丝绸贸易命名，这些路线在1500多年间不仅促进了商业，还促进了文明之间的思想、宗教、技术和疾病的交流。\n\n丝绸之路不是一条单一的道路，而是跨越数千英里的陆路和海路复杂网络。商人为了安全结队旅行。\n\n沿丝绸之路交易的商品改变了两端的社会。中国丝绸、香料、茶叶和瓷器流向西方。比商品更重要的是沿这些路线传播的思想。佛教从印度传播到中国和东亚。造纸技术从中国传播到伊斯兰世界并最终到达欧洲。\n\n丝绸之路也传播了不太受欢迎的旅行者。十四世纪的黑死病可能沿丝绸之路路线从中亚传播到欧洲。丝绸之路仍然是历史上最重要的跨文化交流渠道之一。",
  328, [["What was the Silk Road named after?","A specific road in China","The lucrative Chinese silk trade","A Roman emperor","A type of horse","B","文章指出丝绸之路以利润丰厚的中国丝绸贸易命名。"],["What technology traveled from China to Europe via the Silk Road?","Gunpowder only","Paper-making technology","The printing press","The compass only","B","文章指出造纸技术从中国传播到伊斯兰世界并最终到达欧洲。"],["What disease likely traveled along Silk Road routes to Europe?","Smallpox","Malaria","The Black Death","Cholera","C","文章指出黑死病可能沿丝绸之路路线从中亚传播到欧洲。"],["The word 'lucrative' most likely means:","Dangerous and risky","Producing a great deal of profit","Ancient and outdated","Small and insignificant","B","'lucrative'意为'利润丰厚的、赚钱的'。"]]],
  [139, "The French Revolution", "历史", 2, "The French Revolution, which began in 1789, fundamentally transformed France and had lasting effects on the entire world. It replaced the absolute monarchy that had ruled France for centuries with principles of citizenship, inalienable rights, and the separation of church and state.\n\nThe revolution's causes were deep and complex. France faced a severe financial crisis brought on by costly wars and extravagant royal spending. The social structure divided people into three estates, with the clergy and nobility enjoying privileges and tax exemptions while the common people bore the tax burden. Enlightenment ideas about liberty, equality, and popular sovereignty inspired demands for change.\n\nThe revolution progressed through several phases, each more radical than the last. It began with moderate reforms including the Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen, which proclaimed equal rights and freedom from oppression. The monarchy was abolished and a republic declared. The Reign of Terror, led by Robespierre, saw thousands executed by guillotine, including King Louis XVI and Queen Marie Antoinette.\n\nThe revolution's legacy is profound and contradictory. It established principles of democratic governance and human rights that continue to shape modern societies. However, it also demonstrated how revolutionary idealism can descend into violence and tyranny. Napoleon Bonaparte ultimately seized power, transforming the republic into an empire, yet the revolutionary ideals of liberty, equality, and fraternity endured as powerful forces in world history.",
  "法国大革命于1789年开始，从根本上改变了法国，对整个世界产生了持久影响。它用公民权利、不可剥夺的权利和政教分离的原则取代了统治法国数个世纪的绝对君主制。\n\n革命的原因深远复杂。法国面临严重的金融危机。社会结构将人分为三个等级，教士和贵族享受特权和免税，而普通民众承担税收负担。启蒙运动关于自由、平等和人民主权的思想激发了对变革的要求。\n\n革命经历了几个阶段。它以温和改革开始，包括《人权宣言》。君主制被废除，宣布成立共和国。恐怖统治时期，数千人被断头台处决。\n\n革命的遗产是深远而矛盾的。它确立了民主治理和人权的原则，但也展示了革命理想主义如何沦为暴力和暴政。拿破仑最终夺取了政权，然而自由、平等、博爱的革命理想作为世界历史中的强大力量持续存在。",
  336, [["What principles did the French Revolution establish?","Absolute monarchy","Divine right of kings","Citizenship, inalienable rights, and separation of church and state","Military dictatorship","C","文章指出法国大革命确立了公民权利、不可剥夺的权利和政教分离的原则。"],["What was the social structure called that divided French society?","The class system","The three estates","The caste system","The feudal ranks","B","文章指出社会结构将人分为三个等级（estates）。"],["Who led the Reign of Terror?","Napoleon Bonaparte","King Louis XVI","Robespierre","Marie Antoinette","C","文章指出恐怖统治由罗伯斯庇尔领导。"],["What did the Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen proclaim?","The divine right of kings","Equal rights and freedom from oppression","The supremacy of the nobility","The abolition of all property","B","文章指出《人权宣言》宣布平等权利和免受压迫的自由。"]]],
  [140, "The Industrial Revolution", "历史", 1, "The Industrial Revolution, which began in Britain in the late eighteenth century, transformed economies from agrarian to industrial and fundamentally changed how people lived and worked. It is arguably the most significant economic and social transformation in human history.\n\nSeveral factors enabled Britain to lead the Industrial Revolution. Abundant coal and iron resources provided raw materials for industry. A stable political system protected property rights and encouraged investment. Agricultural improvements freed labor for factory work. Britain's colonial empire provided markets and raw materials. The enclosure movement displaced rural workers who then migrated to cities seeking employment.\n\nKey technological innovations drove industrialization. The steam engine, improved by James Watt, powered factories, transportation, and mining operations. The spinning jenny and power loom revolutionized textile production. Iron and steel manufacturing processes became more efficient, enabling construction of machines, bridges, and railways.\n\nThe social consequences were enormous. Urbanization accelerated as workers crowded into factory towns. Working conditions were often harsh, with long hours, low wages, and dangerous machinery. Child labor was widespread. Environmental pollution from factories degraded air and water quality. Over time, however, industrialization raised living standards, expanded access to goods, and created the middle class. Labor movements eventually secured better working conditions, shorter hours, and the abolition of child labor.",
  "工业革命始于十八世纪后期的英国，将经济从农业转变为工业，从根本上改变了人们的生活和工作方式。它可以说是人类历史上最重要的经济和社会转型。\n\n几个因素使英国领导了工业革命。丰富的煤炭和铁资源提供了工业原料。稳定的政治制度保护产权和鼓励投资。农业改良释放了劳动力。英国殖民地提供了市场和原材料。\n\n关键技术革新推动了工业化。蒸汽机为工厂、运输和采矿提供动力。纺纱机和动力织机彻底改变了纺织生产。\n\n社会后果巨大。城市化加速，工人涌入工厂城镇。工作条件往往恶劣，工时长、工资低、机械危险。童工普遍。然而随着时间的推移，工业化提高了生活水平。劳工运动最终获得了更好的工作条件。",
  334, [["Where did the Industrial Revolution begin?","France","Germany","Britain","The United States","C","文章指出工业革命始于英国。"],["What powered factories and transportation during the Industrial Revolution?","Water wheels","The steam engine improved by James Watt","Electricity","Human labor only","B","文章指出蒸汽机为工厂、运输和采矿提供动力。"],["What was a negative social consequence of industrialization?","Decreased urbanization","Improved working conditions immediately","Harsh working conditions with long hours, low wages, and child labor","Lower production of goods","C","文章指出工作条件往往恶劣，工时长、工资低，童工普遍。"],["What did labor movements eventually secure?","Longer working hours","More child labor","Better working conditions, shorter hours, and abolition of child labor","Lower wages","C","文章指出劳工运动最终获得了更好的工作条件、更短的工时和废除童工。"]]],
  [141, "Ancient Egyptian Civilization", "历史", 1, "Ancient Egypt, one of the world's oldest and most enduring civilizations, flourished along the Nile River for over three thousand years. The predictability of the Nile's annual flooding created fertile agricultural land that sustained a complex and remarkably stable society.\n\nEgyptian society was highly stratified, with the pharaoh at the top as both political and religious leader. Below the pharaoh were priests, nobles, scribes, artisans, and farmers. The afterlife was central to Egyptian religion, and elaborate burial practices including mummification and tomb construction reflected the belief that death was a transition to another existence.\n\nThe achievements of ancient Egypt were remarkable. The Great Pyramids of Giza, built around 2560 BCE, remain among the most impressive architectural feats in human history. Egyptian hieroglyphic writing was one of the earliest writing systems. Advances in medicine, mathematics, astronomy, and engineering demonstrated sophisticated understanding of the natural world.\n\nThe decline of ancient Egypt resulted from both internal and external factors. Periods of political instability, succession crises, and religious conflicts weakened central authority. Foreign invasions by the Assyrians, Persians, and eventually Alexander the Great ended Egyptian independence. Cleopatra VII, the last pharaoh, died in 30 BCE, and Egypt became a province of the Roman Empire. Despite its political end, ancient Egypt's cultural legacy, from monumental architecture to the fascination with mummies and hieroglyphs, continues to captivate the modern world.",
  "古埃及是世界上最古老、最持久的文明之一，在尼罗河沿岸繁荣了三千多年。尼罗河年度洪水的可预测性创造了肥沃的农田，维持了一个复杂而极为稳定的社会。\n\n埃及社会高度分层，法老位于顶端，既是政治领袖也是宗教领袖。来世是埃及宗教的核心，精心制作的葬礼习俗包括木乃伊化和陵墓建造。\n\n古埃及的成就令人瞩目。吉萨大金字塔约建于公元前2560年，至今仍是人类历史上最令人印象深刻的建筑壮举之一。埃及象形文字是最早的文字系统之一。\n\n古埃及的衰落由内外因素导致。政治不稳定、继承危机和宗教冲突削弱了中央权威。外国入侵最终结束了埃及的独立。克利奥帕特拉七世是最后一位法老，于公元前30年去世。尽管政治上终结了，古埃及的文化遗产继续吸引着现代世界。",
  328, [["What geographical feature sustained ancient Egyptian civilization?","The Mediterranean Sea","The Nile River","The Sahara Desert","The Red Sea","B","文章指出古埃及在尼罗河沿岸繁荣了三千多年。"],["What was the pharaoh's role in Egyptian society?","Only a military commander","Both political and religious leader","Only a religious figure","A democratic representative","B","文章指出法老既是政治领袖也是宗教领袖。"],["When were the Great Pyramids of Giza built?","Around 1000 BCE","Around 2560 BCE","Around 500 BCE","Around 4000 BCE","B","文章指出吉萨大金字塔约建于公元前2560年。"],["Who was the last pharaoh of Egypt?","Ramesses II","Nefertiti","Tutankhamun","Cleopatra VII","D","文章指出克利奥帕特拉七世是最后一位法老。"]]],
  [142, "The Renaissance", "历史", 2, "The Renaissance, meaning rebirth, was a cultural movement that began in Italy in the fourteenth century and spread throughout Europe over the next three centuries. It marked a transition from the medieval period to the modern age, reviving interest in classical Greek and Roman art, literature, and philosophy.\n\nSeveral factors contributed to the Renaissance's origins in Italy. Italian city-states like Florence, Venice, and Milan had grown wealthy through trade and banking, providing patronage for artists and scholars. The rediscovery of classical texts, preserved by Islamic scholars and brought to Italy through trade, inspired new ways of thinking. The Byzantine Empire's decline sent Greek scholars westward, bringing knowledge of ancient Greek literature and philosophy.\n\nRenaissance humanism placed emphasis on human potential, individual achievement, and the study of classical texts. This contrasted with the medieval focus on theology and the afterlife. Artists including Leonardo da Vinci, Michelangelo, and Raphael created works that celebrated human beauty and emotion. Writers like Petrarch, Machiavelli, and Shakespeare explored human nature with unprecedented depth.\n\nThe Renaissance extended beyond art and literature. Scientific inquiry advanced through the work of Copernicus, Galileo, and Vesalius, challenging established doctrines. The printing press, invented by Gutenberg around 1440, democratized knowledge by making books affordable and widely available. The Renaissance laid the intellectual foundations for the Scientific Revolution, the Enlightenment, and ultimately the modern world, demonstrating the transformative power of ideas and creativity.",
  "文艺复兴意为「重生」，是始于十四世纪意大利并在此后三个世纪传播到整个欧洲的文化运动。它标志着从中世纪到现代的过渡，恢复了对古典希腊和罗马艺术、文学和哲学的兴趣。\n\n几个因素促成了文艺复兴在意大利的起源。意大利城邦通过贸易和银行业变得富有，为艺术家和学者提供了赞助。古典文献的重新发现激发了新的思维方式。\n\n文艺复兴人文主义强调人的潜能、个人成就和古典文献的研究。艺术家包括达芬奇、米开朗基罗和拉斐尔创作了赞颂人类之美和情感的作品。\n\n文艺复兴超越了艺术和文学。科学探究通过哥白尼、伽利略和维萨里的工作取得了进展。约1440年古腾堡发明的印刷术使书籍变得负担得起和广泛可用。文艺复兴为科学革命、启蒙运动和现代世界奠定了思想基础。",
  330, [["What does the word 'Renaissance' mean?","Darkness","Rebirth","Ending","War","B","文章指出Renaissance意为'重生'。"],["What invention democratized knowledge during the Renaissance?","The telescope","The printing press invented by Gutenberg","The steam engine","The telephone","B","文章指出古腾堡发明的印刷术使书籍变得负担得起和广泛可用。"],["What did Renaissance humanism emphasize?","Theology and the afterlife","Human potential, individual achievement, and study of classical texts","Military conquest","Religious dogma","B","文章指出文艺复兴人文主义强调人的潜能、个人成就和古典文献的研究。"],["Which of these was NOT a Renaissance artist mentioned in the passage?","Leonardo da Vinci","Michelangelo","Raphael","Beethoven","D","文章提到的文艺复兴艺术家包括达芬奇、米开朗基罗和拉斐尔，贝多芬不在其中。"]]],
  [143, "The American Civil War", "历史", 2, "The American Civil War, fought from 1861 to 1865, was the bloodiest conflict in American history. It pitted the Northern states, known as the Union, against the Southern states that seceded to form the Confederacy. The war fundamentally reshaped the United States.\n\nThe primary cause of the Civil War was slavery. The Southern economy depended on slave labor for cotton production, while the North had largely abolished slavery and industrialized. As the United States expanded westward, bitter disputes arose over whether new territories would permit slavery. The election of Abraham Lincoln, who opposed the expansion of slavery, prompted Southern states to secede.\n\nThe war resulted in approximately 620,000 to 750,000 military deaths. Major battles including Gettysburg, Antietam, and Vicksburg claimed enormous casualties. The Emancipation Proclamation, issued by Lincoln in 1863, declared slaves in Confederate states to be free, transforming the war's purpose from preserving the Union to also ending slavery.\n\nThe Union's victory preserved the United States as a single nation and ended slavery with the Thirteenth Amendment. However, the post-war Reconstruction period failed to fully integrate freed slaves into American society. Jim Crow laws enforced racial segregation in the South for nearly a century. The Civil War's legacy continues to influence American politics, race relations, and regional identities, reminding us that the consequences of historical injustices can persist for generations.",
  "美国内战从1861年持续到1865年，是美国历史上最血腥的冲突。它使北方各州（联邦）与脱离联邦组成邦联的南方各州对抗。\n\n内战的主要原因是奴隶制。南方经济依赖奴隶劳动进行棉花生产，而北方已基本废除奴隶制并工业化。随着美国向西扩张，关于新领土是否允许奴隶制的激烈争端出现了。\n\n战争导致约62万至75万军人死亡。1863年林肯发布的《解放奴隶宣言》宣布邦联各州的奴隶获得自由。\n\n联邦的胜利维护了美国的统一，并通过第十三修正案结束了奴隶制。然而战后重建时期未能将获得自由的奴隶完全融入美国社会。吉姆·克劳法在南方执行了近百年的种族隔离。内战的遗产继续影响着美国的政治、种族关系和地区认同。",
  330, [["What was the primary cause of the American Civil War?","Taxation without representation","Slavery","Religious differences","Territory disputes with Mexico","B","文章指出内战的主要原因是奴隶制。"],["What did the Emancipation Proclamation do?","Ended the war","Declared slaves in Confederate states to be free","Gave women the right to vote","Established the income tax","B","文章指出《解放奴隶宣言》宣布邦联各州的奴隶获得自由。"],["Approximately how many military deaths resulted from the Civil War?","About 50,000","About 620,000 to 750,000","About 2 million","About 1 million","B","文章指出战争导致约62万至75万军人死亡。"],["What amendment ended slavery in the United States?","The First Amendment","The Tenth Amendment","The Thirteenth Amendment","The Nineteenth Amendment","C","文章指出第十三修正案结束了奴隶制。"]]],
  [144, "World War I: The Great War", "历史", 2, "World War I, known at the time as the Great War, was a global conflict that lasted from 1914 to 1918 and fundamentally reshaped the twentieth century. It involved most of the world's nations divided into two alliances: the Allies and the Central Powers.\n\nThe war's immediate trigger was the assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria-Hungary in Sarajevo in June 1914. However, deeper causes had been building for decades. A complex system of alliances meant that a conflict between two nations could draw in many others. Militarism, with nations building up massive armies and navies, created an arms race. Imperial competition for colonies and resources generated tensions. Nationalism, particularly in the Balkans, created volatile flashpoints.\n\nThe war introduced devastating new weapons including machine guns, poison gas, tanks, and aircraft. Trench warfare on the Western Front produced unprecedented carnage, with soldiers living in miserable conditions and gaining minimal ground at enormous cost. The Battle of the Somme in 1916 resulted in over one million casualties for minimal territorial gain.\n\nThe war killed approximately 17 million people and wounded another 20 million. The Treaty of Versailles imposed harsh penalties on Germany, creating resentments that would contribute to World War II. The Russian Revolution, the collapse of the Ottoman and Austro-Hungarian empires, and the creation of new nations redrew the map of Europe and the Middle East. The Great War demonstrated that industrialized warfare could produce destruction on a scale previously unimaginable.",
  "第一次世界大战，当时被称为大战，是一场从1914年持续到1918年的全球冲突，从根本上重塑了二十世纪。它涉及世界上大多数国家，分为两个联盟：协约国和同盟国。\n\n战争的直接导火索是1914年6月奥匈帝国弗朗茨·斐迪南大公在萨拉热窝被暗杀。然而更深层的原因已经积累了几十年。复杂的联盟体系意味着两个国家之间的冲突可能卷入许多其他国家。\n\n战争引入了毁灭性的新武器，包括机枪、毒气、坦克和飞机。西线的堑壕战产生了前所未有的屠杀。\n\n战争造成约1700万人死亡，另有2000万人受伤。《凡尔赛条约》对德国施加了严厉的惩罚，产生了促成第二次世界大战的怨恨。大战表明工业化战争可以产生以前无法想象的毁灭规模。",
  334, [["What was the immediate trigger for World War I?","The invasion of Poland","The assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand","The sinking of the Lusitania","The Russian Revolution","B","文章指出战争的直接导火索是弗朗茨·斐迪南大公被暗杀。"],["What type of warfare characterized the Western Front?","Guerilla warfare","Naval warfare","Trench warfare","Aerial warfare","C","文章指出西线的堑壕战产生了前所未有的屠杀。"],["Approximately how many people were killed in World War I?","About 7 million","About 17 million","About 70 million","About 1 million","B","文章指出战争造成约1700万人死亡。"],["What did the Treaty of Versailles do?","Rewarded Germany for its efforts","Imposed harsh penalties on Germany, creating resentments","Created the United Nations","Ended all European empires","B","文章指出《凡尔赛条约》对德国施加了严厉的惩罚，产生了怨恨。"]]],
  [145, "The Cold War", "历史", 2, "The Cold War was a period of geopolitical tension between the United States and the Soviet Union and their respective allies that lasted from approximately 1947 to 1991. Unlike previous major conflicts, the Cold War was characterized by the absence of direct military confrontation between the two superpowers, replaced instead by ideological competition, proxy wars, and nuclear arms races.\n\nThe Cold War emerged from the ashes of World War II. Despite being allies during the war, the United States and Soviet Union had fundamentally different visions for the post-war world. The United States promoted democracy and free-market capitalism, while the Soviet Union sought to spread communism and state-controlled economies. The division of Europe, symbolized by the Berlin Wall, created a physical and ideological Iron Curtain across the continent.\n\nNuclear weapons defined the Cold War. Both superpowers accumulated enormous arsenals of nuclear weapons capable of destroying civilization many times over. The doctrine of mutually assured destruction, or MAD, held that neither side would launch a nuclear attack because the retaliation would be equally devastating. This precarious balance prevented direct conflict but created persistent anxiety about nuclear annihilation.\n\nThe Cold War was fought through proxy wars in Korea, Vietnam, Afghanistan, and elsewhere, costing millions of lives. The Space Race, espionage, propaganda, and economic competition were other fronts. The Cold War ended with the Soviet Union's collapse in 1991, but its legacy continues in geopolitical tensions, nuclear proliferation concerns, and the ongoing influence of Cold War alliances and rivalries.",
  "冷战是大约从1947年持续到1991年美国和苏联及其各自盟友之间的地缘政治紧张时期。与前几次重大冲突不同，冷战的特点是两个超级大国之间没有直接军事对抗，取而代之的是意识形态竞争、代理人战争和核军备竞赛。\n\n冷战从二战的废墟中出现。美国和苏联对战后世界有根本不同的愿景。美国推动民主和自由市场资本主义，而苏联寻求传播共产主义和国家控制的经济。欧洲的分裂，以柏林墙为象征，在欧洲大陆创造了有形和意识形态的铁幕。\n\n核武器定义了冷战。相互确保毁灭的学说认为任何一方都不会发动核攻击，因为报复同样是毁灭性的。\n\n冷战通过在朝鲜、越南、阿富汗等地的代理人战争进行，造成数百万人死亡。冷战以1991年苏联解体而结束，但其遗产仍在继续。",
  332, [["What characterized the Cold War instead of direct military confrontation?","Peaceful cooperation","Ideological competition, proxy wars, and nuclear arms races","Economic collaboration only","Religious harmony","B","文章指出冷战的特点是意识形态竞争、代理人战争和核军备竞赛。"],["What did MAD stand for?","Military Action Directive","Mutually assured destruction","Maximum Armament Deployment","Missile Attack Detection","B","文章指出MAD代表相互确保毁灭（mutually assured destruction）。"],["When did the Cold War end?","1945","1969","1985","1991","D","文章指出冷战以1991年苏联解体而结束。"],["What symbolized the division of Europe during the Cold War?","The Maginot Line","The Berlin Wall","Hadrian's Wall","The Great Wall","B","文章指出欧洲的分裂以柏林墙为象征。"]]],
  [146, "The Age of Exploration", "历史", 1, "The Age of Exploration, spanning roughly from the fifteenth to the seventeenth century, was a period when European nations sent voyages across the world's oceans in search of new trade routes, territories, and knowledge. These expeditions reshaped global trade, initiated European colonialism, and connected previously isolated civilizations.\n\nSeveral motivations drove European exploration. The Ottoman Empire's control of overland trade routes to Asia made spices and other goods expensive, creating demand for alternative sea routes. The desire for wealth through trade and precious metals was powerful. Christian nations sought to spread their religion. Technological advances including the compass, improved cartography, and better ship designs like the caravel made long ocean voyages feasible.\n\nPortugal and Spain led early exploration. Portuguese navigators including Vasco da Gama sailed around Africa to reach India, establishing a sea route to Asian spice markets. Christopher Columbus, sailing for Spain in 1492, reached the Americas, though he believed he had found Asia. Ferdinand Magellan's expedition completed the first circumnavigation of the globe, demonstrating the Earth's vast size.\n\nThe consequences of exploration were transformative and often devastating. The Columbian Exchange transferred plants, animals, and diseases between hemispheres, with European diseases killing an estimated 90 percent of indigenous populations in the Americas. The transatlantic slave trade forcibly transported approximately 12 million Africans to the New World. European colonization displaced native civilizations and extracted enormous wealth. The Age of Exploration created the interconnected world we inhabit today, but its legacy of exploitation and cultural destruction remains deeply consequential.",
  "大航海时代大约从十五世纪持续到十七世纪，是欧洲国家派遣航海家穿越世界海洋寻找新贸易路线、领土和知识的时期。这些远征重塑了全球贸易，开启了欧洲殖民主义，并连接了以前孤立的文明。\n\n几个动机推动了欧洲的探索。奥斯曼帝国控制了通往亚洲的陆路贸易路线，使香料等商品价格昂贵，创造了对替代海路的需求。对通过贸易和贵金属获取财富的渴望是强大的。\n\n葡萄牙和西班牙领导了早期的探索。葡萄牙航海家达伽马绕过非洲到达印度。1492年为西班牙航行的哥伦布到达了美洲。麦哲伦的远征完成了首次环球航行。\n\n探索的后果是变革性的，往往是毁灭性的。哥伦布大交换在半球之间转移了植物、动物和疾病，欧洲疾病估计杀死了美洲90%的土著人口。跨大西洋奴隶贸易强行将约1200万非洲人运送到新世界。大航海时代创造了我们今天居住的互联世界，但其剥削和文化毁灭的遗产仍然具有深远影响。",
  338, [["What was a key motivation for European exploration?","Desire for isolation","Ottoman control of overland trade routes making Asian goods expensive","Fear of the ocean","Religious persecution in Europe","B","文章指出奥斯曼帝国控制了陆路贸易路线，使亚洲商品价格昂贵，创造了对替代海路的需求。"],["Who completed the first circumnavigation of the globe?","Christopher Columbus","Vasco da Gama","Ferdinand Magellan","Marco Polo","C","文章指出麦哲伦的远征完成了首次环球航行。"],["What percentage of indigenous populations in the Americas did European diseases kill?","About 10%","About 50%","About 90%","About 30%","C","文章指出欧洲疾病估计杀死了美洲90%的土著人口。"],["How many Africans were forcibly transported to the New World?","About 1.2 million","About 12 million","About 120 million","About 120,000","B","文章指出跨大西洋奴隶贸易强行将约1200万非洲人运送到新世界。"]]],
  [147, "Ancient Greek Democracy", "历史", 1, "Ancient Greece, particularly the city-state of Athens in the fifth century BCE, is credited with creating the world's first known democracy. This system of government, in which citizens participated directly in political decision-making, laid the foundations for democratic governance that would influence civilizations for millennia.\n\nAthenian democracy was direct rather than representative. All male citizens over the age of eighteen could attend the Assembly, where they debated and voted on laws, foreign policy, and important public decisions. Offices were filled by lottery rather than election for most positions, reflecting the belief that any citizen was capable of governance. A Council of 500, chosen by lot, prepared the agenda for the Assembly.\n\nThe democracy excluded significant portions of the population. Women, slaves, and foreign residents were denied citizenship and political participation. Of an estimated population of 300,000 in Athens, only about 30,000 were citizens with full political rights. Slavery was integral to the system, as slave labor freed citizens to participate in politics.\n\nDespite its limitations, Athenian democracy achieved remarkable outcomes. It fostered a culture of public debate, civic engagement, and individual freedom that produced extraordinary achievements in philosophy, drama, architecture, and the arts. The works of Socrates, Plato, and Aristotle examined questions of governance, justice, and the good life that continue to inform political thought. The democratic experiment in Athens demonstrated that ordinary citizens could govern themselves, an idea that would inspire revolutions and constitutions across the centuries.",
  "古希腊，特别是公元前五世纪的雅典城邦，被认为创造了世界上最早的已知民主制度。这种公民直接参与政治决策的政府制度为民主治理奠定了基础，影响了数千年来的文明。\n\n雅典民主是直接民主而非代议制民主。所有十八岁以上的男性公民都可以参加公民大会，在那里辩论和投票决定法律、外交政策和重要的公共决策。大多数职位通过抽签而非选举填补。\n\n该民主制度排除了大量人口。妇女、奴隶和外邦居民被剥夺了公民身份和政治参与。在雅典约30万人口中，只有约3万人是拥有完全政治权利的公民。\n\n尽管有局限性，雅典民主取得了显著成果。它培育了公共辩论、公民参与和个人自由的文化，产生了哲学、戏剧、建筑和艺术方面的非凡成就。苏格拉底、柏拉图和亚里士多德的著作继续为政治思想提供信息。",
  328, [["What type of democracy did Athens have?","Representative democracy","Direct democracy where citizens participated in decision-making","Military dictatorship","Constitutional monarchy","B","文章指出雅典民主是直接民主而非代议制民主。"],["How were most offices filled in Athenian democracy?","By election","By lottery or sortition","By inheritance","By military rank","B","文章指出大多数职位通过抽签而非选举填补。"],["What percentage of Athens' population were citizens with full political rights?","About 1%","About 10%","About 50%","About 90%","B","文章指出在约30万人口中，只有约3万人是公民，约占10%。"],["Who was excluded from Athenian citizenship?","Only slaves","Women, slaves, and foreign residents","Only the poor","Only criminals","B","文章指出妇女、奴隶和外邦居民被剥夺了公民身份。"]]],
  [148, "The Mongol Empire", "历史", 2, "The Mongol Empire, founded by Genghis Khan in 1206, became the largest contiguous land empire in history, stretching from Korea to Hungary at its height. In less than a century, the Mongols conquered more territory than the Romans acquired in four centuries, fundamentally altering the course of Eurasian history.\n\nGenghis Khan, originally named Temujin, unified the nomadic Mongol tribes through a combination of military prowess, diplomatic skill, and ruthless determination. He reorganized Mongol society on a decimal military system, created an elite bodyguard called the Kheshig, and promoted officers based on merit rather than birth. This meritocratic approach gave the Mongols a significant advantage over hereditary aristocracies.\n\nMongol military success stemmed from several factors. Their cavalry was unmatched in speed and mobility, capable of covering vast distances rapidly. Their composite bows were devastatingly effective. They employed sophisticated tactics including feigned retreats, encirclement, and psychological warfare. They also adopted and adapted technologies from conquered peoples, including siege engines from China and the Islamic world.\n\nThe Mongol Empire facilitated the largest exchange of goods, ideas, and technologies between East and West until modern times. The Pax Mongolica, a period of relative peace under Mongol rule, made the Silk Road safe for travelers. However, Mongol conquests were also extraordinarily destructive, with an estimated 30 to 40 million people killed. The Black Death may have spread along Mongol trade routes. The empire fragmented after Genghis Khan's death, but its impact on world history was permanent.",
  "蒙古帝国由成吉思汗于1206年建立，成为历史上最大的连续陆地帝国，鼎盛时期从朝鲜延伸到匈牙利。在不到一个世纪的时间里，蒙古人征服的领土比罗马人在四个世纪中获得的还多。\n\n成吉思汗，原名铁木真，通过军事力量、外交技巧和无情决心的结合统一了游牧蒙古部落。他根据功绩而非出身来提拔军官。这种精英制方法给了蒙古人显著优势。\n\n蒙古军事成功源于几个因素。他们的骑兵在速度和机动性方面无可匹敌。他们采用复杂的战术，包括佯装撤退、包围和心理战。\n\n蒙古帝国促进了东西方之间直到现代以前最大规模的商品、思想和技术交流。蒙古治下的相对和平使丝绸之路对旅行者安全。然而蒙古征服也极其破坏性，估计有3000万至4000万人被杀。帝国在成吉思汗去世后分裂，但其对世界历史的影响是永久的。",
  330, [["Who founded the Mongol Empire?","Kublai Khan","Genghis Khan","Attila the Hun","Tamerlane","B","文章指出蒙古帝国由成吉思汗于1206年建立。"],["What was the Pax Mongolica?","A Mongol religious ceremony","A period of relative peace under Mongol rule that made the Silk Road safe","A Mongol military strategy","A type of Mongol food","B","文章指出蒙古治下的相对和平使丝绸之路对旅行者安全。"],["How did the Mongols promote officers?","Based on noble birth only","Based on merit rather than birth","Based on wealth","Based on age","B","文章指出成吉思汗根据功绩而非出身来提拔军官。"],["Approximately how many people were killed during Mongol conquests?","About 3 to 4 million","About 30 to 40 million","About 300 million","About 300,000","B","文章指出估计有3000万至4000万人被杀。"]]],
  [149, "The Opium Wars in China", "历史", 2, "The Opium Wars were two conflicts between China and Western powers in the nineteenth century that had profound consequences for China's sovereignty and development. These wars marked the beginning of what Chinese historians call the century of humiliation.\n\nIn the early nineteenth century, Britain faced a significant trade imbalance with China. British consumers demanded Chinese tea, silk, and porcelain, but China wanted few British goods in return. To reverse the outflow of silver, British merchants began smuggling opium from India into China. By the 1830s, millions of Chinese had become addicted, causing severe social and economic problems.\n\nThe Qing government's efforts to suppress the opium trade led to the First Opium War from 1839 to 1842. China's military was no match for British naval power and modern weapons. The resulting Treaty of Nanjing forced China to cede Hong Kong to Britain, open five treaty ports to foreign trade, pay large indemnities, and grant extraterritorial rights to British citizens.\n\nThe Second Opium War from 1856 to 1860 involved Britain and France against China. It ended with more concessions, including the legalization of the opium trade, opening of additional ports, and permission for foreign missionaries to travel freely throughout China. The Opium Wars weakened the Qing Dynasty, triggered domestic rebellions including the Taiping Rebellion that killed an estimated 20 to 30 million people, and began China's long struggle to modernize and reclaim its sovereignty.",
  "鸦片战争是十九世纪中国与西方列强之间的两次冲突，对中国的主权和发展产生了深远后果。这些战争标志着中国历史学家所称的百年耻辱的开始。\n\n十九世纪初，英国面临与中国的严重贸易逆差。英国消费者需要中国茶叶、丝绸和瓷器，但中国几乎不需要英国商品。为了扭转白银外流，英国商人开始从印度向中国走私鸦片。到1830年代，数百万中国人上瘾。\n\n清政府取缔鸦片贸易的努力导致了1839年至1842年的第一次鸦片战争。中国军事不是英国海军力量和现代武器的对手。由此产生的《南京条约》迫使中国割让香港、开放五个通商口岸、支付巨额赔款。\n\n第二次鸦片战争从1856年持续到1860年。鸦片战争削弱了清朝，引发了国内叛乱，包括造成约2000万至3000万人死亡的太平天国运动，并开始了中国现代化和恢复主权的漫长斗争。",
  334, [["Why did British merchants smuggle opium into China?","To cure Chinese diseases","To reverse the trade imbalance and outflow of silver","To help the Chinese economy","At the Chinese government's request","B","文章指出为了扭转白银外流，英国商人开始向中国走私鸦片。"],["What did the Treaty of Nanjing force China to do?","Close all ports to foreign trade","Cede Hong Kong, open treaty ports, and pay indemnities","Invade Britain","Stop producing tea","B","文章指出《南京条约》迫使中国割让香港、开放通商口岸和支付赔款。"],["What domestic rebellion followed the Opium Wars?","The Boxer Rebellion","The Taiping Rebellion","The Cultural Revolution","The Ming Restoration","B","文章指出引发了包括太平天国运动在内的国内叛乱。"],["How many people died in the Taiping Rebellion?","About 2 to 3 million","About 20 to 30 million","About 200 million","About 200,000","B","文章指出太平天国运动造成约2000万至3000万人死亡。"]]],
  [150, "The Civil Rights Movement", "历史", 1, "The Civil Rights Movement in the United States, which peaked in the 1950s and 1960s, was a struggle by African Americans to end racial segregation and discrimination and achieve equal rights under the law. It remains one of the most significant social movements in American history.\n\nFollowing the Civil War and the abolition of slavery, Southern states enacted Jim Crow laws enforcing racial segregation in schools, transportation, restaurants, and other public facilities. African Americans faced systematic discrimination in voting, employment, housing, and education. Lynchings and racial violence terrorized Black communities. Despite constitutional guarantees of equality, the reality was one of pervasive racial oppression.\n\nThe movement employed both legal challenges and nonviolent direct action. In 1954, the Supreme Court's Brown v. Board of Education ruling declared school segregation unconstitutional. Rosa Parks' refusal to give up her bus seat in 1955 sparked the Montgomery Bus Boycott. Martin Luther King Jr. emerged as the movement's most prominent leader, advocating nonviolent resistance inspired by Gandhi.\n\nLandmark achievements included the Civil Rights Act of 1964, which outlawed discrimination based on race, color, religion, sex, or national origin, and the Voting Rights Act of 1965, which prohibited racial discrimination in voting. Despite these legal victories, racial inequality persists in many forms. The movement's legacy continues to inspire struggles for justice and equality around the world, demonstrating the power of organized, principled resistance to oppressive systems.",
  "美国民权运动在1950年代和1960年代达到高潮，是非洲裔美国人结束种族隔离和歧视并争取法律下平等权利的斗争。它仍然是美国历史上最重要的社会运动之一。\n\n内战和废除奴隶制后，南方各州颁布了吉姆·克劳法，在多个领域执行种族隔离。非洲裔美国人在投票、就业、住房和教育方面面临系统性歧视。\n\n该运动采用法律挑战和非暴力直接行动。1954年最高法院布朗诉教育委员会案裁定学校种族隔离违宪。1955年罗莎·帕克斯拒绝让出公交车座位引发了蒙哥马利公交车抵制运动。马丁·路德·金成为该运动最杰出的领袖，倡导受甘地启发的非暴力抵抗。\n\n里程碑成就包括1964年《民权法案》和1965年《投票权法案》。尽管取得了这些法律胜利，种族不平等仍以多种形式存在。该运动的遗产继续激励着世界各地的正义和平等斗争。",
  326, [["What did Jim Crow laws enforce?","Equal rights for all","Racial segregation in public facilities","Women's suffrage","Religious freedom","B","文章指出南方各州颁布了吉姆·克劳法，执行种族隔离。"],["What did the Brown v. Board of Education ruling declare?","That slavery was constitutional","That school segregation was unconstitutional","That voting rights should be restricted","That bus segregation was legal","B","文章指出布朗诉教育委员会案裁定学校种族隔离违宪。"],["Who was the most prominent leader of the Civil Rights Movement?","Malcolm X","Rosa Parks","Martin Luther King Jr.","John F. Kennedy","C","文章指出马丁·路德·金成为该运动最杰出的领袖。"],["What did the Civil Rights Act of 1964 outlaw?","Voting for women","Discrimination based on race, color, religion, sex, or national origin","Immigration","All forms of taxation","B","文章指出1964年《民权法案》禁止基于种族、肤色、宗教、性别或民族血统的歧视。"]]],
  [151, "The Viking Age", "历史", 1, "The Viking Age, spanning roughly from 793 to 1066 CE, was a period when Scandinavian Norsemen explored, raided, traded, and settled across Europe, the North Atlantic, and even reached North America. The Vikings left an enduring mark on the lands they encountered, shaping the political, cultural, and linguistic landscape of medieval Europe.\n\nSeveral factors drove Viking expansion. Overpopulation in Scandinavia created pressure for new lands. Political consolidation pushed out those who resisted centralized authority. Advances in shipbuilding, particularly the development of the longship with its shallow draft and sail, enabled Norse sailors to navigate both open oceans and shallow rivers. Climate change may have also played a role, as the Medieval Warm Period made northern navigation more feasible.\n\nThe Vikings were not merely raiders. They were also traders, explorers, and settlers who established communities from Greenland to Constantinople. Viking traders connected Scandinavia with the Islamic world, Byzantine Empire, and Western Europe. They founded cities including Dublin, Novgorod, and Reykjavik. Leif Erikson reached North America around the year 1000, nearly 500 years before Columbus.\n\nViking influence extended to language, law, and governance. English words including sky, egg, law, and window derive from Old Norse. The Normans, descendants of Vikings who settled in northern France, would go on to conquer England in 1066. The Viking Age ended as Scandinavian kingdoms converted to Christianity and adopted more centralized forms of government, integrating into the broader European political order.",
  "维京时代大约从公元793年持续到1066年，是斯堪的纳维亚北欧人探索、袭击、贸易和定居的时期，足迹遍布欧洲、北大西洋，甚至到达北美。维京人对他们遇到的土地留下了持久的印记。\n\n几个因素推动了维京扩张。斯堪的纳维亚的人口过剩造成了新土地的压力。造船业的进步，特别是吃水浅的长船的发展，使北欧水手能够航行于开阔的海洋和浅河。\n\n维京人不仅是袭击者。他们也是商人、探险家和定居者。维京商人将斯堪的纳维亚与伊斯兰世界、拜占庭帝国和西欧连接起来。莱夫·埃里克森大约在1000年到达北美，比哥伦布早近500年。\n\n维京影响延伸到语言、法律和治理。包括sky、egg、law和window在内的英语单词源自古诺尔斯语。诺曼人是定居在法国北部的维京人后裔，于1066年征服了英格兰。",
  324, [["What technological advancement enabled Viking navigation?","The compass","The longship with shallow draft and sail","The steam engine","The telescope","B","文章指出长船的发展使北欧水手能够航行于开阔海洋和浅河。"],["Who reached North America around the year 1000?","Christopher Columbus","Leif Erikson","Marco Polo","Vasco da Gama","B","文章指出莱夫·埃里克森大约在1000年到达北美。"],["Which of these English words derives from Old Norse?","Liberty","Democracy","Sky","Justice","C","文章指出包括sky在内的英语单词源自古诺尔斯语。"],["When did the Viking Age approximately end?","793 CE","1000 CE","1066 CE","1492 CE","C","文章指出维京时代大约从793年持续到1066年。"]]],
  [152, "The Russian Revolution", "历史", 2, "The Russian Revolution of 1917 was one of the most consequential events of the twentieth century, overthrowing the centuries-old Romanov dynasty and establishing the world's first communist state. It would shape global politics for the next seventy years and beyond.\n\nPrerevolutionary Russia was characterized by extreme inequality. The tsar held absolute power, while the vast majority of Russians were impoverished peasants. Rapid industrialization created an urban working class enduring terrible conditions. Russia's involvement in World War I strained the economy and military, with massive casualties eroding public support for the tsarist regime.\n\nThe revolution unfolded in two phases. The February Revolution toppled the tsar and established a provisional government. However, this government's decision to continue the war proved deeply unpopular. In October, the Bolsheviks, led by Vladimir Lenin, seized power with the promise of peace, land for peasants, and workers' control of industry.\n\nThe Bolsheviks faced enormous challenges, including a devastating civil war from 1918 to 1922. The Red Army, led by Leon Trotsky, ultimately defeated the White forces and foreign interventions. The Soviet Union, formally established in 1922, became a one-party state under communist rule. Joseph Stalin's rise to power after Lenin's death in 1924 brought forced collectivization, rapid industrialization, and political purges that killed millions. The Russian Revolution demonstrated both the appeal of radical equality and the dangers of totalitarian governance.",
  "1917年俄国革命是二十世纪最重要的事件之一，推翻了数百年的罗曼诺夫王朝，建立了世界上第一个共产主义国家。\n\n革命前的俄罗斯以极端不平等为特征。沙皇拥有绝对权力，而绝大多数俄罗斯人是贫困的农民。俄国参与一战使经济和军事承受巨大压力。\n\n革命分为两个阶段。二月革命推翻了沙皇并建立了临时政府。然而该政府继续参战的决定极其不得人心。十月，布尔什维克在列宁的领导下夺取了政权。\n\n布尔什维克面临巨大挑战，包括1918年至1922年的毁灭性内战。红军最终击败了白军和外国干预。1922年正式成立的苏维埃联盟成为共产党统治下的一党制国家。斯大林在列宁去世后上台带来了强制集体化、快速工业化和政治清洗，导致数百万人死亡。",
  328, [["What did the Russian Revolution overthrow?","A democratic government","The centuries-old Romanov dynasty","The Soviet Union","A military dictatorship","B","文章指出俄国革命推翻了数百年的罗曼诺夫王朝。"],["Who led the Bolsheviks during the October Revolution?","Joseph Stalin","Leon Trotsky","Vladimir Lenin","Karl Marx","C","文章指出布尔什维克在列宁的领导下夺取了政权。"],["What promises did the Bolsheviks make?","More war and higher taxes","Peace, land for peasants, and workers' control of industry","Democracy and free markets","Religious reform","B","文章指出布尔什维克承诺和平、给农民土地和工人控制工业。"],["What did Stalin's rule bring after Lenin's death?","Democratic reforms","Forced collectivization, rapid industrialization, and political purges","Peace and prosperity","Religious freedom","B","文章指出斯大林上台带来了强制集体化、快速工业化和政治清洗。"]]],
  [153, "The Ming Dynasty's Maritime Expeditions", "历史", 2, "During the early fifteenth century, the Chinese Ming Dynasty launched a series of extraordinary maritime expeditions that rivaled and in many ways surpassed the European voyages of exploration that would follow decades later. These expeditions, led by the admiral Zheng He, demonstrated China's technological and organizational superiority but were ultimately abandoned.\n\nZheng He commanded seven voyages between 1405 and 1433, leading massive fleets that were the largest the world had ever seen. The treasure ships, the largest vessels, were estimated to be over 120 meters long, far exceeding European ships of the era. The fleets carried approximately 27,000 personnel including sailors, soldiers, diplomats, and interpreters.\n\nThe expeditions traveled throughout Southeast Asia, across the Indian Ocean to India, the Persian Gulf, and the East African coast. Zheng He established diplomatic relations, collected tribute, and projected Chinese power across the maritime world. Unlike European explorers who came later, China sought not to conquer or colonize but to demonstrate the Ming Dynasty's glory and bring foreign states into the tributary system.\n\nAfter the Yongle Emperor's death, Confucian officials who viewed the expeditions as wasteful and unnecessary gained influence. The Ming Dynasty turned inward, banning oceanic voyages and restricting foreign trade. The technological knowledge required to build such fleets was lost. This fateful decision, made just as Europe was beginning its age of exploration, altered the course of world history. Had China continued its maritime expansion, the global balance of power might have developed very differently.",
  "十五世纪初期，中国明朝发动了一系列非凡的海上远征，在许多方面超过了数十年后欧洲的探索航行。这些由郑和领导的远征展示了中国的技术和组织优势，但最终被放弃。\n\n郑和在1405年至1433年间指挥了七次远航，率领了世界前所未见的最大舰队。宝船估计超过120米长，远超当时欧洲船只。\n\n远征队航行遍及东南亚，穿越印度洋到达印度、波斯湾和东非海岸。郑和建立了外交关系并展示了明朝的威望。与后来的欧洲探险家不同，中国寻求的不是征服或殖民，而是展示明朝的荣耀。\n\n永乐帝去世后，认为远征浪费和不必要的儒家官员获得了影响力。明朝转向内敛，禁止海洋航行并限制对外贸易。建造此类舰队所需的技术知识丢失了。这一重大决定改变了世界历史的进程。",
  332, [["How many voyages did Zheng He command?","Three","Five","Seven","Ten","C","文章指出郑和指挥了七次远航。"],["How large were Zheng He's treasure ships estimated to be?","About 30 meters long","About 60 meters long","About 120 meters long","About 200 meters long","C","文章指出宝船估计超过120米长。"],["Why were the expeditions abandoned?","Because China was conquered","Because Confucian officials viewed them as wasteful and the Ming Dynasty turned inward","Because the ships were destroyed in storms","Because Zheng He died on the last voyage","B","文章指出认为远征浪费的儒家官员获得了影响力，明朝转向内敛。"],["How did China's purpose differ from later European explorers?","China sought to colonize more aggressively","China sought to demonstrate glory and bring states into the tributary system, not to conquer or colonize","China only wanted to spread religion","China wanted to start wars","B","文章指出中国寻求的不是征服或殖民，而是展示明朝的荣耀并将外国纳入朝贡体系。"]]],
  [154, "The Decline and Fall of the Ottoman Empire", "历史", 2, "The Ottoman Empire, which lasted from 1299 to 1922, was one of the longest-lasting and most powerful empires in history. At its height, it controlled much of Southeast Europe, Western Asia, and North Africa. Its decline, often called the Sick Man of Europe, spanned centuries and reshaped the modern Middle East.\n\nSeveral factors contributed to Ottoman decline. Military defeats, particularly the failed siege of Vienna in 1683, marked the end of Ottoman expansion in Europe. Economic stagnation resulted from the shift of trade routes to the Atlantic after European discoveries. The empire's diverse population of different religions and ethnicities became increasingly difficult to govern as nationalism spread. Corruption and inefficiency weakened central authority.\n\nThe nineteenth century brought further challenges. European powers intervened in Ottoman affairs, supporting independence movements among Christian populations. The empire lost territory through wars and nationalist uprisings in the Balkans, Greece, and Egypt. The Crimean War and the Congress of Berlin highlighted the empire's vulnerability. Attempts at modernization, known as the Tanzimat reforms, achieved limited success against entrenched interests.\n\nWorld War I proved fatal to the Ottoman Empire. Allying with the Central Powers, the empire suffered defeat, and its remaining territories were partitioned by the victorious Allies. The Armenian Genocide during the war remains one of history's darkest chapters. Mustafa Kemal Ataturk led the Turkish War of Independence, establishing the Republic of Turkey in 1923. The empire's dissolution created new nations and conflicts in the Middle East that continue to the present day.",
  "奥斯曼帝国从1299年持续到1922年，是历史上最持久和最强大的帝国之一。在鼎盛时期，它控制了东南欧、西亚和北非的大部分地区。它的衰落跨越了数个世纪，重塑了现代中东。\n\n几个因素导致了奥斯曼的衰落。军事失败，特别是1683年维也纳围攻失败，标志着奥斯曼在欧洲扩张的终结。欧洲发现后贸易路线转移到大西洋导致经济停滞。民族主义的传播使帝国内不同宗教和种族的人口越来越难以治理。\n\n十九世纪带来了更多挑战。欧洲列强干预奥斯曼事务，支持基督教人口的独立运动。帝国通过战争和民族主义起义失去了领土。现代化尝试取得有限成功。\n\n一战对奥斯曼帝国是致命的。与同盟国结盟的帝国遭受失败，剩余领土被战胜的协约国瓜分。战争期间的亚美尼亚种族灭绝仍然是历史上最黑暗的篇章之一。穆斯塔法·凯末尔·阿塔图尔克领导了土耳其独立战争，于1923年建立了土耳其共和国。帝国的解体创造了中东的新国家和持续至今的冲突。",
  338, [["How long did the Ottoman Empire last?","From 1299 to 1453","From 1299 to 1922","From 1453 to 1922","From 1000 to 1800","B","文章指出奥斯曼帝国从1299年持续到1922年。"],["What marked the end of Ottoman expansion in Europe?","The conquest of Constantinople","The failed siege of Vienna in 1683","The Crimean War","The Tanzimat reforms","B","文章指出1683年维也纳围攻失败标志着奥斯曼在欧洲扩张的终结。"],["Who established the Republic of Turkey?","Suleiman the Magnificent","Mustafa Kemal Ataturk","Omar Khayyam","T.E. Lawrence","B","文章指出穆斯塔法·凯末尔·阿塔图尔克建立了土耳其共和国。"],["What was the Ottoman Empire often called during its decline?","The Sleeping Giant","The Sick Man of Europe","The Eastern Dragon","The Golden Empire","B","文章指出奥斯曼帝国的衰落常被称为'欧洲病夫'。"]]],
  [155, "The Inca Empire", "历史", 1, "The Inca Empire was the largest empire in pre-Columbian America, stretching along the western coast of South America from modern-day Colombia to Chile. At its height in the early sixteenth century, it encompassed approximately 12 million people speaking many different languages across vastly diverse geographical regions.\n\nThe Inca achieved remarkable feats of engineering and administration. They built an extensive road system spanning over 40,000 kilometers through mountains, deserts, and jungles. Messengers called chasquis relayed information across the empire at remarkable speed. The Inca had no written language but used an intricate system of knotted cords called quipu for record-keeping and communication.\n\nAgricultural innovation was crucial to feeding the empire's large population. The Inca developed sophisticated terracing and irrigation systems that allowed farming on steep mountain slopes. They cultivated potatoes, maize, and quinoa at various altitudes, and built storehouses to preserve food for times of shortage.\n\nThe Spanish conquest, led by Francisco Pizarro in 1532, brought the empire to a devastating end. Pizarro captured the Inca emperor Atahualpa and executed him despite receiving a massive ransom. European diseases, against which the Inca had no immunity, killed far more people than Spanish weapons. The conquest destroyed one of the most sophisticated civilizations in the Americas, yet Inca cultural elements including their language, Quechua, agricultural practices, and communal traditions survive among millions of descendants today.",
  "印加帝国是前哥伦布时期美洲最大的帝国，沿着南美洲西海岸从今天的哥伦比亚延伸到智利。在十六世纪初的鼎盛时期，它涵盖了约1200万人。\n\n印加人取得了非凡的工程和行政成就。他们建造了超过4万公里的广泛道路系统。他们没有书面语言，但使用称为奇普的复杂绳结系统进行记录和交流。\n\n农业创新对养活帝国大量人口至关重要。印加人发展了复杂的梯田和灌溉系统。他们在不同海拔种植土豆、玉米和藜麦，并建造仓库储存食物。\n\n1532年由弗朗西斯科·皮萨罗领导的西班牙征服给帝国带来了毁灭性的结局。欧洲疾病杀死了远比西班牙武器更多的人。征服摧毁了美洲最精密的文明之一，但印加文化元素包括其语言克丘亚语、农业实践和社区传统至今仍在数百万后裔中存续。",
  326, [["How long was the Inca road system?","About 4,000 kilometers","About 40,000 kilometers","About 400 kilometers","About 400,000 kilometers","B","文章指出印加人建造了超过4万公里的道路系统。"],["What did the Inca use for record-keeping?","Written books","An intricate system of knotted cords called quipu","Stone tablets","Papyrus scrolls","B","文章指出印加人使用称为奇普的复杂绳结系统进行记录。"],["Who led the Spanish conquest of the Inca Empire?","Hernan Cortes","Francisco Pizarro","Christopher Columbus","Vasco Nunez de Balboa","B","文章指出由弗朗西斯科·皮萨罗领导的西班牙征服。"],["What killed more Inca people than Spanish weapons?","Famine","Civil war","European diseases","Earthquakes","C","文章指出欧洲疾病杀死了远比西班牙武器更多的人。"]]],
  [156, "The Partition of India", "历史", 2, "The Partition of India in 1947 was one of the most traumatic events in modern history, dividing British India into two independent nations: Hindu-majority India and Muslim-majority Pakistan. The partition displaced approximately 15 million people and triggered sectarian violence that killed between one and two million.\n\nBritish colonial rule had shaped the conditions for partition. The British policy of divide and rule exacerbated religious tensions between Hindus and Muslims. The Muslim League, led by Muhammad Ali Jinnah, demanded a separate nation for Muslims, while the Indian National Congress, led by Jawaharlal Nehru and Mahatma Gandhi, sought a united India. Despite Gandhi's efforts to maintain unity, the demand for Pakistan gained overwhelming support among Muslims.\n\nThe partition was executed with devastating haste. The British government, eager to withdraw, assigned Sir Cyril Radcliffe to draw the boundary lines despite his never having visited India. He had just five weeks to determine the borders between the two nations. His decisions placed millions of people on the wrong side of the new borders, triggering one of the largest mass migrations in human history.\n\nThe human cost was staggering. As Hindus and Sikhs moved to India and Muslims to Pakistan, communal violence erupted along the migration routes. Trains carrying refugees arrived at their destinations filled with murdered passengers. Women were abducted and assaulted on both sides. Entire communities that had coexisted for centuries turned on each other. The trauma of partition continues to affect relations between India and Pakistan, two nuclear-armed nations that have fought multiple wars since independence.",
  "1947年印巴分治是现代历史上最创伤性的事件之一，将英属印度分为两个独立国家：印度教徒占多数的印度和穆斯林占多数的巴基斯坦。分治使约1500万人流离失所，引发的宗派暴力造成100万至200万人死亡。\n\n英国殖民统治塑造了分治的条件。英国的分而治之政策加剧了印度教徒和穆斯林之间的宗教紧张关系。穆斯林联盟要求为穆斯林建立独立国家，而印度国大党寻求统一的印度。\n\n分治以毁灭性的速度执行。英国政府指派西里尔·拉德克利夫爵士划定边界，尽管他从未到过印度。他只有五周时间确定两国边界。他的决定将数百万人置于新边界的错误一侧。\n\n人员代价惊人。印度教徒和锡克教徒迁往印度，穆斯林迁往巴基斯坦时，迁徙路线上爆发了社区暴力。分治的创伤继续影响印度和巴基斯坦之间的关系，这两个拥有核武器的国家自独立以来已打过多次战争。",
  330, [["How many people were displaced during the Partition of India?","About 1.5 million","About 15 million","About 150 million","About 15,000","B","文章指出分治使约1500万人流离失所。"],["How long did Sir Cyril Radcliffe have to draw the boundary lines?","Five months","Five weeks","Five days","Five years","B","文章指出他只有五周时间确定边界。"],["What British policy exacerbated religious tensions?","Direct rule","Divide and rule","Free trade","Religious tolerance","B","文章指出英国的分而治之政策加剧了宗教紧张关系。"],["How many people were killed in partition violence?","About 10,000 to 50,000","About 100,000 to 500,000","About one to two million","About ten million","C","文章指出宗派暴力造成100万至200万人死亡。"]]
]];
